<div id="review_3621365982" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3621365982" />
    <a title="axel." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/119514392-axel"><img alt="axel." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626568016p2/119514392.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3621365982?book_show_action=true">Nov 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="axel." class="user" itemprop="url" name="axel." href="/user/show/119514392-axel">axel.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3621365982" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer566903178365602706">Blood, Sperm, Alcohol, Sex, Drugs, Disgust... - The morality, good taste and correctness thrown by the discharge<br/><br/>First of all, this book is not for everyone, it is extremely immoral, wrong, problematic, graphic. And so, in my view, he is focused on his own niche, which is gothic and horror literature.<br/><br/> * sighing *<br/><br/>Okay, come on, this was my first gothic/horror book and it was a very bizarre journey throughout history. It looks like that typical macabre and bloody book, but it goes further, it simpl</span>
  <span id="freeText566903178365602706" style="display:none">Blood, Sperm, Alcohol, Sex, Drugs, Disgust... - The morality, good taste and correctness thrown by the discharge<br /><br />First of all, this book is not for everyone, it is extremely immoral, wrong, problematic, graphic. And so, in my view, he is focused on his own niche, which is gothic and horror literature.<br /><br /> * sighing *<br /><br />Okay, come on, this was my first gothic/horror book and it was a very bizarre journey throughout history. It looks like that typical macabre and bloody book, but it goes further, it simply atrophies and/or destroys what we say is right for society. Literally throughout the book, events become more violent and immoral (sorry, but I think I'll use that word a lot here) showing the courageous and disgusting content that the author makes.<br /><br />I will put some quotes that I found interesting:<br /><br /> • "...but he couldn't label it with words as wrong or bad. He wondered if he ever knew what those words meant..."<br /><br /> • "They found that even in the face of pain that seems unbearable, even in the face of the pain that pulls the last drop of blood from your heart and leaves your scrimshaw embroidery inside your skull, life goes on. And the pain becomes opaque and begins to disappear. "<br /><br /> • "I don't think anyone knows what evil is. I don't think anyone has the right to say."<br /><br />Explaining a little about the story, Lost Souls follows Zillah, Molochai, Twig - who are vampires; Christian who is also a vampire; Ghost and Steve; and Nothing - a gothic teenager who has a peculiar personality. I liked the narration and the writing, which are really the highlights for me. It's practically about Nothing looking to find something to connect with and didn't feel alone. It's about Ghost and Steve with their band and private dramas. It's about Zillah, Molochai and Twig doing carnage, drinking and fucking men and women. And by the way, the plot totally brings the bisexual atmosphere in sex and flirtations.<br /><br />Thousands of situations bothered me and I was super uncomfortable, and that sounded purposeful to me, being to provoke revulsion, anxiety and shock the reader. However, the "naturalization" of pre-teens and teenagers having sex, using drugs... were some of those things that made me very uncomfortable. I even try to understand that the author possibly wanted to pass this on to represent this gothic and horror culture (I'm a bit of a layman on this topic, but I like it, so I read this book out of curiosity).<br /><br />In addition, there is heavy incest, rape and graphic violence. Regarding graphic violence, at times I found it free, but due to being vampires, the brutal form of acts for food and delight is relevant.<br /><br />So, in some moments I imagined an alternative reality for this story, I couldn't imagine how "real life" with the supernatural plus of magic, sometimes it sounded very absurd, you know...<br /><br />I think there is no way to write about the barbarities, the immorality and all the bloody shit that this book brings and throws in your face. And, as you may have noticed, I "liked" the book, but for all the context, the language, the rot that it proposes, but with all possible reservations. And for sure, I will read other books by the author.<br /><br />Remembering that this book is not for everyone, if you have any kind of TW with these themes, please do not read. This book is graphic, dirty and all the worst appellations for a horror story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="566903178365602706" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

