        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2861521851" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11944593720375480871"><i>I can take pain. It will pass. And if I choose to return and take my pain out of your hide, I will. Or, if you like, I’ll shove my tongue down your throat and corrupt you with my spit. Or, if you prefer, I’ll unzip your skin and kiss you with your own heart-blood on my lips. Are you tempted yet?</i><br/><br/>actual rating: 3.5<br/><br/>This ...was certainly a time. It definitely captures that ~gothic teenage angst~ feeling very well, and although at 29 years old I find it all more than a bit ridiculous I would have bee</span>
  <span id="freeText11944593720375480871" style="display:none"><i>I can take pain. It will pass. And if I choose to return and take my pain out of your hide, I will. Or, if you like, I’ll shove my tongue down your throat and corrupt you with my spit. Or, if you prefer, I’ll unzip your skin and kiss you with your own heart-blood on my lips. Are you tempted yet?</i><br /><br />actual rating: 3.5<br /><br />This ...was certainly a time. It definitely captures that ~gothic teenage angst~ feeling very well, and although at 29 years old I find it all more than a bit ridiculous I would have been SO into this when I was 16. While it is very obvious that Brite wrote this while still a teenager himself it is actually pretty well written, if a bit over the top much of the time. There is a lot of messed up stuff in here so I'll do my best to give you a trigger warning list - I don't think I could have read this if I hadn't known all of it beforehand - but I do want to to single out one thing first. <br /><br />While I enjoyed this overall, the reason I rounded it down is because I just cannot in good conscience rate a book more than 3 stars if every single woman in it gets raped and dies giving birth. That might seem hypocritical since I gave Exquisite Corpse 4 stars and there were no women in that at all, but I can see why there would not be women in a book that uses murder as a metaphor for the AIDS crisis and would honestly rather women were not present at all than to be included to be very minor characters and be treated the way they were here.<br /><br />Other than the whole 'three entire female characters, only one of whom is actually alive in the present timeline or for more than a few pages, who are all raped and die giving birth to vampire babies because wow what a hot take right there' mess, there is also parent/child incest [between a father and teenage daughter that comes with the added gross factor of her being the one to 'seduce' him and then also between a father and teenage son who decide that it's fine since they're vampires and that makes it not count I guess?] as well as just a lot of underage sex in general [the main character is 15] and a woman who is raped by her ex-boyfriend after she breaks up with him. <br /><br />I don't necessarily know WHY I liked this book so much considering all of the above, but I guess sometimes it is interesting to think of the [generally misguided] attitudes that you had as a teenager and become a bit nostalgic for that time in your life even though I think I would genuinely slap my teenage self if I ever met her lol. This is definitely something for the edgy teenage goth crowd, and also probably for people who think that Anne Rice isn't messed up or explicit enough ;)</span>
  <a data-text-id="11944593720375480871" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

